This paper deals with social choice theory, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science that studies how to aggregate individual preferences into a collective decision. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses utility functions, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The authors use mathematical proofs to establish their results, which suggests that the paper could also be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper proposes a probabilistic social choice function, which could be relevant to the sub-category cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
